I'm an American, and I've wanted a 406 Coupe since they came out in the 90's. I moved to eastern Europe a couple of years ago, and I bought one.

It is a beautiful car. I still admire mine when I walk up to it in a parking lot. I think that in the US, where most people have never seen one, you may get people thinking it's a Ferrari or some other very expensive car. To me, it feels like a very big car compared to the others I own, but, compared to American cars, it's not big. I think it would be very nice to drive on the more generously sized American roads. It's also an excellent cruiser that is very quiet at high speeds with great directional stability and suspension that soaks up bumps while still feeling planted. Mine has the 2.2L diesel (with a tune), and it just cruises quietly and effortlessly at 90 mph while having a good reserve of power for passing and still delivering high 30's mpg.

On the downside, the interior is pretty cramped. I'm not a tall guy, but my seven year old daughter complains about leg room if she sits behind me. I swear a Ford Fiesta has more room inside. There isn't much interior storage (pockets, cubbies, etc.), and the cupholders are jokes, and if you want an armrest (rare and relatively expensive part but also chinzy and cheap feeling) you lose the cupholders and make the interior feel more cramped. The power seats can't be adjusted by adult sized hands when the doors are closed. Also, while the chassis is great for long distance cruising, it is definitely not sporty. If there's a word that is the opposite of "tossable", that would be a good description.

I haven't mentioned maintenance. In the US, you'll be on your own. There are good troubleshooting guides online. You should probably buy a laptop with PP2000/Lexia installed on it. International shipping is a thing, but it's an old car, and Peugeot has stopped making some parts for which there may not be aftermarket replacements.
